# Project Architecture

```text
Developer Pushes Code to GitHub
            ↓
        Jenkins Pipeline
            ↓
 Build Docker Images for Services
            ↓
 Push Images to Amazon ECR
            ↓
 Deploy to Amazon EKS
            ↓
 Access Application via LoadBalancer
```

---

# Microservices Used

* auth-service
* chat-service
* admin-service
* streaming-service
* streaming-frontend

---

# Implementation Steps

## Step 1: Source Code Management

* Forked / cloned the project repository from GitHub.
* Managed project source code using Git.

## Step 2: Dockerization

Created Docker images for:

* auth-service
* chat-service
* admin-service
* streaming-service
* streaming-frontend

Sample command:

```bash
docker build -t auth-service ./backend/authService
```

---

## Step 3: Amazon ECR Setup

Created repositories in Amazon ECR and pushed images.

Sample commands:

```bash
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name auth-service

docker push <account-id>.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/auth-service:latest
```

---

## Step 4: Jenkins CI/CD Pipeline

Installed Jenkins on AWS EC2 instance.

Pipeline stages:

* Clone Source Code
* Build Docker Images
* Authenticate with ECR
* Push Images to ECR

---

## Step 5: Kubernetes Deployment using Amazon EKS

Created EKS cluster using eksctl.

```bash
eksctl create cluster --name streaming-cluster-v2 --region ap-south-1 --nodes 2 --node-type t3.medium
```

Verified cluster:

```bash
kubectl get nodes
```

---

## Step 6: Application Exposure

Frontend deployed using Kubernetes Service type LoadBalancer.

```bash
kubectl expose deployment streaming-frontend --type=LoadBalancer --port=80 --target-port=80
```

Accessed application successfully through external browser URL.

---

